4. Project Work and Methodology
The development of EventRush followed an iterative methodology, focusing on building and testing core features in distinct phases.
1.	Phase 1: Database Design and Setup: The project began by defining the data structure. Two primary schemas were designed using Mongoose:
o	User Schema: To store username, email, and a hashed password.
o	Event Schema: To store event details like title, sport, description, date, location, imageUrl, and an array of participants. A free-tier cluster was set up on MongoDB Atlas to host the database.
2.	Phase 2: Backend API Development: Using Node.js and Express.js, a RESTful API was constructed with two main sets of endpoints:
o	Authentication Routes (/api/auth): Endpoints for user registration (/register) and login (/login). The registration process includes password hashing with bcrypt.js, and a successful login returns a JWT for authenticating future requests.
o	Event Routes (/api/events): Endpoints to fetch all events, retrieve a single event by its ID, and allow a user to participate in an event. The participation endpoint is protected by an authentication middleware that verifies the user's JWT.
3.	Phase 3: Frontend Development and Integration: The user interface was built with three primary HTML pages (index.html, events.html, login.html) and later extended with event-details.html.
o	Vanilla JavaScript was used to make asynchronous API calls to the backend using the fetch() API.
o	Dynamic content rendering was implemented to display event cards on the main events page and detailed information on the event-specific page.
o	User interactions, such as form submissions for login/registration and button clicks for participation, were handled, with feedback provided to the user.



5. Results
The project successfully resulted in a fully functional prototype of the EventRush web application. The final product achieves all the primary objectives set at the outset.
The key implemented features are:
•	Secure User Authentication: Users can create an account and log in securely. The system stores hashed passwords and uses JWTs to manage user sessions, ensuring that actions like event participation are protected.
•	Dynamic Event Listings: The application fetches event data from the MongoDB database and displays it dynamically, ensuring the information is always up-to-date.
•	Detailed Event View: Users can click on any event to navigate to a dedicated page that provides comprehensive details, including a description, date, location, and the number of participants.
•	Event Participation System: Authenticated users can register for an event with a single click. The system prevents a user from registering for the same event multiple times.
•	Modern and Responsive UI: The application features a clean, modern design with animations and is responsive, providing a consistent user experience on both desktop and mobile browsers.


6. Conclusion
This project was a comprehensive exercise in full-stack web development, successfully delivering a practical solution to a real-world problem. The EventRush application demonstrates the effective use of the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express.js, Node.js, with Vanilla JS on the frontend) to build a dynamic, database-driven web application. The development process provided invaluable hands-on experience in API design, database management, user authentication, and the integration of frontend and backend systems. The final product stands as a robust proof-of-concept that is both functional and scalable.


7. Future Scope of Development
While the current version of EventRush is a complete prototype, there are numerous avenues for future enhancement to transform it into a feature-rich, production-ready application.
•	User Profiles: A dedicated user dashboard where users can view the events they have registered for and manage their profile information.
•	Advanced Search and Filtering: Implementing a search bar and filters to allow users to find events by sport, date range, location, or keywords.
•	Event Creation for Organizers: Introducing a new user role ("Organizer") who can submit and manage their own events through a dedicated portal.
•	Notifications System: Integrating email or browser notifications to remind registered users about upcoming events.
•	Social Integration: Allowing users to share events they are interested in on social media platforms to increase community engagement.
